data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically on .NET 8. **No migration is needed** for this code.

That said, for modern .NET you'd typically replace raw threads with `Task.Run` + `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
    await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
}
```

This gives you better thread-pool usage and simpler cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
